BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:México City AI\, Machine Learning and Computer Vision Meetup|May 
 14 - AI\, ML and Computer Vision Meetup|Online
DTSTART:20260514T100000
CATEGORIES:ai,backend,data,devops,frontend,mobile,web
DESCRIPTION:México City AI\, Machine Learning and Computer Vision Meetup\
 nJoin our virtual meetup to hear talks from experts on cutting-edge topics
  across AI\, ML\, and computer vision.\n\n**Day\, Time\, Location**\n\nMay
  14\, 2026\n9:00-11:00 AM Pacific\nOnline. **[Register for the Zoom!](http
 s://voxel51.com/events/ai-ml-and-computer-vision-meetup-may-14-2026)**\n\n
 **Concept-Aware Batch Sampling Improves Language-Image Pretraining**\n\nWh
 at data should a vision-language model be trained on\, and who gets to dec
 ide what “good data” even means? Most existing curation pipelines are 
 limited because they are offline (they produce a static dataset from a set
  of predetermined filtering criteria) and concept-agnostic (they rely on m
 odel-based scores that can silently introduce new biases in what concepts 
 the model sees). In this talk\, I will discuss our new work CABS that tack
 les both these problems with large-scale sample-level concept annotations 
 and flexible online batch sampling.\n\nFirst\, we construct DataConcept\, 
 a 128M web-crawled image–text collection annotated with fine-grained con
 cept composition\, and show how this enables Concept-Aware Batch Sampling 
 (CABS)—a simple online method that constructs training batches on-the-fl
 y to match target concept distributions. We develop two variants\, CABS-DM
  for maximizing concept coverage and CABS-FM for prioritizing high object 
 multiplicity\, and demonstrate consistent gains for CLIP/SigLIP-style mode
 ls across 28 benchmarks.\n\nFinally\, I’ll show that these improvements 
 translate into strong vision encoders for training generative multimodal m
 odels\, including autoregressive systems like LLaVA\, where the encoder qu
 ality materially affects downstream capability.\n\n*About the Speaker*\n\n
 [Adhiraj Ghosh](https://www.linkedin.com/in/adhiraj-ghosh/) is a first yea
 r ELLIS PhD student\, working with Matthias Bethge at The University of T
 übingen. He completed his undergraduate degree in Electrical and Electron
 ics Engineering jointly at the Manipal Institute of Technology and SMU Sin
 gapore from 2016 to 2020\, and his masters in Machine Learning at The Univ
 ersity of Tübingen from 2022 to 2024.\n\n**Do Your Agents Actually Work? 
 Measuring Skills and MCP in Practice**\n\nThis talk shows how to evaluate 
 agent performance in real scenarios using FiftyOne Skills and MCP. We will
  cover practical ways to design scenarios\, run agents\, and measure how t
 hey use tools\, including signals like latency\, token usage\, and output 
 quality. The goal is to move beyond final outputs and better understand ag
 ent behavior\, helping teams build more reliable and measurable agent syst
 ems.\n\n*About the Speaker*\n\n[Adonai Vera](https://www.linkedin.com/in/a
 donai-vera/) \\- Machine Learning Engineer & DevRel at Voxel51\\. With ove
 r 7 years of experience building computer vision and machine learning mode
 ls using TensorFlow\, Docker\, and OpenCV\\.\n\n**The last mile of OCR [in
  2026]**\n\nOCR is nailing it in benchmarks but the real work lies in The 
 Long Tail of IDP. Large tables\, old scans\, mixed-language docs\, handwri
 ting\, complex layouts is where most enterprise and real-world document wo
 rk happens. This is where the best benchmarked models still struggle. In t
 his talk\, we will go through how LandingAI’s Agentic Document Extractio
 n (ADE) goes beyond OCR and Parsing to enable real-world document AI use c
 ases and workloads.\n\nWe'll cover:\n\n* The pillars of Agentic Document E
 xtraction\n* Building document processing pipelines with ADE API/SDK\n* Us
 ing Skills to have Coding Agents build for you\n* How ADE gives LLMs the l
 ast mile - Analysing LLM performance on large table\, scanned docs\, compl
 ex layouts and enabling them with the structured output from ADE\n\n*About
  the Speaker*\n\n[Ankit Khare](https://www.linkedin.com/in/deeplearnerak) 
 has been building Developer Relations function at high-growth startups lik
 e Rockset (a world-class retrieval system\, later acquired by OpenAI)\, Tw
 elve Labs (a video intelligence startup backed by Index Ventures\, Radical
  Ventures\, and NEA)\, and Abacus.AI (an AI Super Assistant backed by Inde
 x Ventures\, Eric Schmidt\, and Ram Shriram). Before that\, he was an AI e
 ngineer at third insight and an AI researcher at the LEARN Lab at UT-Arlin
 gton\, working on visual scene understanding and image captioning agents.\
 n\n**The Energy Layer of AI: Powering the Next Wave of Inference**\n\nThe 
 talk explores how inference cost fundamentally ties to energy at scale\, e
 specially as the AI industry shifts toward always-on\, agent-driven worklo
 ads\, and the focus moved from training to inference economics. Medi will 
 share lessons and observations from his team's R&D efforts in making AI wo
 rkloads grid-aware\, energy-intelligent\, and dynamically optimized in rea
 l time.\n\n*About the Speaker*\n\n[Medi Naseri](https://www.linkedin.com/i
 n/mnaserim/) is the Founder and CEO of LōD Technologies\, where he leads 
 the development of energy-intelligent infrastructure for flexible data cen
 ters and the broader compute ecosystem.\nWith a PhD in Electrical Engineer
 ing specializing in control and power systems\, Medi brings deep technical
  expertise to the challenge of scaling AI within real-time grid constraint
 s.
LOCATION:Online
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:AI/IA CDMX|El Turista Tiene Alma\, el Algoritmo No - The Tourist H
 as a Soul\, the Algorithm D|México|Ciudad de México
DTSTART:20260519T180000
CATEGORIES:ai,frontend,security
DESCRIPTION:AI/IA CDMX (Ciudad de México Inteligencia Artificial)\nSpani
 sh with live English subtitles\nEste evento será en español con subtítu
 los en inglés en vivo.\n\\*\\*Presencial y en vivo en YouTube/In-person a
 nd live on YouTube:\\*\\*\nhttps://www.youtube.com/@AICDMX\n\nEnglish Vers
 ion Below\n\n6:00 p.m. Apertura y registro\n6:30 p.m. Arranca la conversac
 ión\n7:15 p.m. Preguntas y respuestas con el público\n7:30 p.m. Networki
 ng\n8:00–9:30 p.m. After party en un lugar cercano (a 5 min caminando\; 
 hay\nespacio interior/exterior\, trae chamarra y zapatos para comer y bebe
 r)\n\nViajar siempre ha sido algo personal. A dónde vas\, por qué vas\, 
 qué buscas cuando llegas. Las respuestas son distintas para cada quien. P
 ero durante décadas\, la industria ha tratado a los viajeros como segment
 os en una hoja de cálculo. La AI finalmente está haciendo posible la per
 sonalización real. La pregunta es si la vamos a usar para diseñar viajes
  con significado\, o simplemente embudos más eficientes.\n\nMireya Nieto 
 es la fundadora de Hey Priya y ha estado trabajando en la intersección de
  AI\, viajes y experiencia humana. En esta charla\, explora qué significa
  diseñar experiencias de viaje en la era de la inteligencia artificial. N
 o solo recomendar destinos\, sino entender las motivaciones más profundas
  detrás de por qué la gente viaja y cómo la tecnología puede servir a 
 esas motivaciones sin aplanarlas.\n\n\\#\\# Vamos a explorar\n\n• \\*\\*
 Personalización más allá de preferencias.\\*\\* Ir más allá de "te gu
 stó París\, prueba Roma" hacia entender qué es lo que realmente busca e
 l viajero\n\n• \\*\\*AI como partner de diseño.\\*\\* Cómo la AI puede
  dar forma a viajes que se sienten intencionales\, no algorítmicos\n\n•
  \\*\\*La experiencia humana al centro.\\*\\* Por qué el mejor travel con
  AI mantiene la historia humana al frente\, no la métrica de optimizació
 n\n\n• \\*\\*Construir donde la emoción importa.\\*\\* Qué tiene de di
 ferente diseñar productos de AI donde el resultado no es eficiencia\, sin
 o significado\n\n\\#\\# Sobre Mireya\nhttps://www.linkedin.com/in/mireya-n
 ieto/\nMireya Nieto · Fundadora\, Hey Priya\n\n\\*\\*Schedule\\*\\*\n6:00
  p.m. Doors & check-in\n6:30 p.m. Conversation begins\n7:15 p.m. Audience 
 Q&A\n7:30 p.m. Networking\n8:00–9:30 p.m. After party at a nearby spot (
 5 min walk\; indoor/outdoor\, bring a jacket and your drinking/eating shoe
 s)\n\nTravel has always been personal. Where you go\, why you go\, what yo
 u're looking for when you get there. Those answers are different for every
 one. But for decades\, the industry has treated travelers like segments in
  a spreadsheet. AI is finally making real personalization possible. The qu
 estion is whether we'll use it to design meaningful journeys\, or just mor
 e efficient funnels.\n\nMireya Nieto is the founder of Hey Priya and has b
 een working at the intersection of AI\, travel\, and human experience. In 
 this talk\, she explores what it means to design travel experiences in the
  age of artificial intelligence. Not just recommending destinations\, but 
 understanding the deeper motivations behind why people travel and how tech
 nology can serve those motivations without flattening them.\n\n\\#\\# We'l
 l explore\n\n• \\*\\*Personalization beyond preferences.\\*\\* Moving pa
 st "you liked Paris\, try Rome" toward understanding what a traveler is ac
 tually seeking\n\n• \\*\\*AI as a design partner.\\*\\* How AI can shape
  journeys that feel intentional\, not algorithmic\n\n• \\*\\*The human e
 xperience at the center.\\*\\* Why the best AI-powered travel keeps the hu
 man story front and center\, not the optimization metric\n\n• \\*\\*Buil
 ding in a space where emotion matters.\\*\\* What's different about design
 ing AI products where the output isn't efficiency\, but meaning\n\n\\#\\# 
 About Mireya\nhttps://www.linkedin.com/in/mireya-nieto/\nMireya Nieto · F
 ounder\, Hey Priya
LOCATION:Casa Rafael Galván\, Zacatecas 94\, Col Roma Norte\,\, Mexico Ci
 ty\, Mexico City
X-CRONQUILES-ADDRESS:Zacatecas 94\, Roma Nte.\, Cuauhtémoc\, 06700 Ciudad
  de México\, CDMX\, México
X-CRONQUILES-CITY:Ciudad de México
X-CRONQUILES-CITY-CODE:cdmx
X-CRONQUILES-COUNTRY:México
X-CRONQUILES-COUNTRY-CODE:MX
