BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:México City AI\, Machine Learning and Computer Vision Meetup|May 
 20 - Getting Started with FiftyOne|Online
DTSTART:20260520T110000
CATEGORIES:ai,cloud,data,frontend,python
DESCRIPTION:México City AI\, Machine Learning and Computer Vision Meetup\
 nThis workshop provides a technical foundation for managing large scale co
 mputer vision datasets. You will learn to curate\, visualize\, and evaluat
 e models using the [open source FiftyOne app](https://docs.voxel51.com/).\
 n\n**Date\, Time and Location**\n\nMay 20\, 2026\n10 AM PST - 11 AM Pacifi
 c\nOnline. **[Register for the Zoom!](https://voxel51.com/events/getting-s
 tarted-with-fiftyone-may-20-2026)**\n\nThe session covers data ingestion\,
  embedding visualization\, and model failure analysis. You will build work
 flows to identify dataset bias\, find annotation errors\, and select infor
 mative samples for training. Attendees leave with a framework for data cen
 tric AI for research and production pipelines\, prioritizing data quality 
 over pure model iteration.\n\nWhat you'll learn\n\n* **Structure unstructu
 red data.** Map data and metadata into a queryable schema for images\, vid
 eos\, and point clouds.\n* **Query datasets with the FiftyOne SDK**. Creat
 e complex views based on model predictions\, labels\, and custom tags. Use
  the FiftyOne to filter data based on logical conditions and confidence sc
 ores.\n* **Visualize high dimensional embeddings**. Project features into 
 lower dimensions to find clusters of similar samples. Identify data gaps a
 nd outliers using FiftyOne Brain.\n* **Automate data curation.** Implement
  algorithmic measures to select diverse subsets for training. Reduce label
 ing costs by prioritizing high entropy samples.\n* **Debug model performan
 ce.** Run evaluation routines to generate confusion matrices and precision
  recall curves. Visualize false positives and false negatives directly in 
 the App to understand model failures.\n* **Customize FiftyOne**. Build cus
 tom dashboards and interactive panels. Create specialized views for domain
  specific tasks.\n\n**Prerequisites:**\n\n* Working knowledge of Python an
 d machine learning and/or computer vision fundamentals.\n* All attendees w
 ill get access to the tutorials and code examples used in the workshop.
LOCATION:Online
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:México City AI\, Machine Learning and Computer Vision Meetup|May 
 21 - Women in AI Meetup|Online
DTSTART:20260521T100000
CATEGORIES:ai,data,frontend,mobile,python
DESCRIPTION:México City AI\, Machine Learning and Computer Vision Meetup\
 nHear talks from experts on the latest topics in AI\, ML\, and computer vi
 sion on May 21.\n\n**Date\, Time and Location**\n\nMay 21\, 2026\n9 - 11 A
 M pacific\nOnline. **[Register for the Zoom!](https://voxel51.com/events/w
 omen-in-ai-meetup-may-21-2026)**\n\n**Beyond Models: LLM-Guided Reinforcem
 ent Learning for Real-World Wireless Systems**\n\nReinforcement learning a
 gents often perform well in simulation but break down when deployed in rea
 l\, non-stationary\, constraint-driven environments such as wireless syste
 ms. This work explores using large language models not as annotators or re
 ward hacks\, but as a reasoning layer that guides RL decision-making with 
 domain logic\, scenario interpretation\, and adaptive constraints.\n\nWe p
 resent an architecture where the LLM provides structured\, high-level advi
 sory signals while the RL policy remains the final action authority to avo
 id hallucination-driven failures. Early experiments show that this hybrid 
 setup improves robustness under distribution shifts and complex constraint
  scenarios where standard RL collapses. The goal is not to replace RL with
  LLMs\, but to combine learning and reasoning into a more deployable contr
 ol-intelligence framework.\n\n*About the Speaker*\n\n[Fatemeh Lotfi ](http
 s://www.linkedin.com/in/fatemeh-lotfi-1a860359/?skipRedirect=true)is a Ph.
 D. researcher focused on integrating large language models and reinforceme
 nt learning for adaptive wireless control systems. Her work targets the li
 mitations of classical RL under real-world uncertainty by introducing reas
 oning-driven guidance mechanisms using LLMs. She has contributed to multip
 le AI-for-infrastructure projects\, including advanced O-RAN automation.\n
 \n**Responsible and Ethical AI in Healthcare: Building Trustworthy and Inc
 lusive Intelligent Systems**\n\nIn this session\, I will discuss how Respo
 nsible AI principles: including fairness\, transparency\, accountability\,
  and reliability can be practically embedded into healthcare AI systems. K
 ey discussion points will include:\n\n* Addressing bias and equity challen
 ges in healthcare datasets and model training.\n* Building explainable and
  interpretable AI to strengthen clinician trust and adoption.\n* Ensuring 
 ethical deployment of generative AI models within regulated healthcare env
 ironments.\n* Establishing governance frameworks for data privacy\, model 
 monitoring\, and regulatory compliance.\n\n*About the Speaker*\n\n[Jahnavi
  Kachhia](https://www.linkedin.com/in/jk186/?skipRedirect=true) is the Glo
 bal Product Owner\, AI & ML at Abbott\, leading large-scale AI initiatives
  for the FreeStyle Libre platform to enhance clinical decision-making and 
 patient outcomes. Previously at Meta’s Reality Labs\, she advanced AR/VR
  innovation and LLM-based intelligent systems. An active contributor to th
 e AI research community\, she serves on the IJCAI 2025 Program Committee a
 nd reviews for AAAI\, IJCNN\, and IEEE conferences.\n\n**AI Applications i
 n Drug Repurposing**\n\nDrug repurposing is increasingly important because
  it offers a faster\, lower-cost path to therapeutic discovery compared to
  de novo drug development\, especially in oncology where many cancers stil
 l lack effective targeted options. In under-studied cancers such as endome
 trial cancer\, the challenge is often a lack of large\, high-quality clini
 cal or response datasets\, making purely data-dependent approaches difficu
 lt to scale reliably. This motivates combining data-independent strategies
  (e.g.\, pathway- and mechanism-driven modeling) with data-dependent learn
 ing when interaction evidence is available. A practical and scalable direc
 tion is drug–target interaction (DTI) prediction\, where AI models can l
 everage molecular and protein representations to prioritize mechanisticall
 y plausible drug candidates for repurposing.\n\n*About the Speaker*\n\n[Ma
 dhurima Mondal's](https://www.linkedin.com/in/madhurima-mondal-65a59882/) 
 academic journey has been shaped by strong foundations in mathematical and
  scientific problem-solving\, including multiple national-level achievemen
 ts such as Regional Mathematics Olympiad (RMO)\, NTSE\, and the KVPY fello
 wship. She completed my B.Tech and M.Tech in Electronics & Electrical Comm
 unication Engineering from IIT Kharagpur\, and I am currently a PhD candid
 ate in Electrical & Computer Engineering at Texas A&M University\,
LOCATION:Online
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:AI/IA CDMX|IoT: El Espía Que Me Compré - IoT: The Spy I Bought M
 yself|México|Ciudad de México
DTSTART:20260616T180000
CATEGORIES:ai,data,frontend,mobile,python,security,web
DESCRIPTION:AI/IA CDMX (Ciudad de México Inteligencia Artificial)\nSpani
 sh with live English subtitles\nEste evento será en español con subtítu
 los en inglés en vivo.\n**Presencial y en vivo en YouTube/In-person and l
 ive on YouTube:**\nhttps://www.youtube.com/@AICDMX\n\nEnglish Version Belo
 w\n\n6:00 p.m. Apertura y registro\n6:30 p.m. Arranca la conversación\n7:
 15 p.m. Preguntas y respuestas con el público\n7:30 p.m. Networking\n8:00
 –9:30 p.m. After party en un lugar cercano (a 5 min caminando\; hay\nesp
 acio interior/exterior\, trae chamarra y zapatos para comer y beber)\n\nTu
  refrigerador sabe qué comes. Tu reloj sabe cuánto duermes. Tu bocina in
 teligente escucha más de lo que crees. El Internet de las Cosas llenó nu
 estras casas y oficinas de dispositivos que recopilan datos sin parar. La 
 mayoría de nosotros firmó los términos y condiciones sin leer una líne
 a. Pero alguien sí tiene que leerlos. Y alguien tiene que escribir los qu
 e todavía no existen.\n\nLeonardo Morales es abogado especializado en cib
 erseguridad y protección de datos personales. En esta plática\, arranca 
 desde lo básico: qué es el IoT\, por qué genera riesgos reales para tu 
 privacidad\, y qué marcos legales ya existen para obligar a que la cibers
 eguridad proteja tus datos. No es una plática de paranoia. Es una de real
 idad. Porque las regulaciones ya están ahí\, y la mayoría de la gente q
 ue diseña\, construye o usa esta tecnología no las conoce.\n\n## Vamos a
  explorar\n\n• **IoT sin el humo.** Qué es realmente el Internet de las
  Cosas\, cómo funciona la recopilación de datos y por qué la privacidad
  nunca vuelve a ser la misma\n\n• **Tus datos\, su negocio.** Qué infor
 mación capturan los dispositivos conectados\, quién accede a ella y qué
  tan expuesto estás sin saberlo\n\n• **La ley como primera línea de de
 fensa.** Regulaciones que ya exigen ciberseguridad como herramienta de pro
 tección de datos personales\, con ejemplos concretos\n\n• **Lo que falt
 a por escribirse.** Dónde están los huecos legales y qué debería impor
 tarnos como usuarios\, desarrolladores y ciudadanos\n\n## Sobre Leonardo\n
 https://www.linkedin.com/in/leonardo-morales-abogado-de-la-guarda/\nLeonar
 do Morales · Director de Área Legal-Corporativa\, Consultoría Xaman Eck
 \n\n**Schedule**\n6:00 p.m. Doors & check-in\n6:30 p.m. Conversation begin
 s\n7:15 p.m. Audience Q&A\n7:30 p.m. Networking\n8:00–9:30 p.m. After pa
 rty at a nearby spot (5 min walk\; indoor/outdoor\, bring a jacket and you
 r drinking/eating shoes)\n\nYour fridge knows what you eat. Your watch kno
 ws how you sleep. Your smart speaker listens more than you think. The Inte
 rnet of Things filled our homes and offices with devices that collect data
  around the clock. Most of us signed the terms and conditions without read
 ing a single line. But someone has to read them. And someone has to write 
 the ones that don't exist yet.\n\nLeonardo Morales is a lawyer specializin
 g in cybersecurity and personal data protection. In this talk\, he starts 
 from the ground up: what IoT actually is\, why it creates real risks for y
 our privacy\, and what legal frameworks already exist to make cybersecurit
 y a tool for protecting your data. This isn't a paranoia talk. It's a real
 ity check. The regulations are already there\, and most people designing\,
  building\, or using this technology don't know them.\n\n## We'll explore\
 n\n• **IoT without the smoke.** What the Internet of Things actually is\
 , how data collection works\, and why privacy is never the same after\n\n
 • **Your data\, their business.** What information connected devices cap
 ture\, who gets access\, and how exposed you are without knowing it\n\n•
  **The law as the first line of defense.** Regulations that already requir
 e cybersecurity as a data protection tool\, with concrete examples\n\n• 
 **What still needs to be written.** Where the legal gaps are and why they 
 should matter to users\, developers\, and citizens\n\n## About Leonardo\nh
 ttps://www.linkedin.com/in/leonardo-morales-abogado-de-la-guarda/\nLeonard
 o Morales · Director of Corporate Legal\, Consultoría Xaman Eck
LOCATION:Casa Rafael Galván\, Zacatecas 94\, Col Roma Norte\,\, Mexico Ci
 ty\, Mexico City
